node.text: Recently, Copine (@copineproject) celebrated their fifth anniversary – and shared that they will reopen for dine-in service on July 15! Designed by principal/owner Kirsten Ring Murray (@kirsten3000), Copine features a balance of traditional and modern, reclaimed and new, to create a refined, human-scaled space where their contemporary American cuisine takes center stage. We’ve enjoyed Copine’s takeaway suppers throughout this past year, and we can’t wait to visit for an in-person meal again soon. Visit link in bio to learn more!

node.text: “The significance of history doesn't garner much attention in contemporary architectural dialogue, but in the case of the Space Needle, it was a critical and constant baseline for our decisions. Our approach was more subtractive than additive, peeling away the many decades of additions and modifications that deviated from the purity of the original 1962 design.” –Alan Maskin, Design Principal. Learn more about the Space Needle’s (@spaceneedle) history and renovation in the new film, Space Needle Looking Upwards – visit link in bio to watch now on Amazon Prime!

node.text: “As an architect, it’s not really about the building,” says Tom Kundig, FAIA, RIBA, Design Principal. “It’s about how it shapes the space and what people are doing in the space. I just love watching the kids get all worked up about the dinosaurs and stuff.” We’re very excited to share that the Burke Museum is reopening on September 22, allowing kids of all ages to once again view its wide-ranging collection of natural and cultural artifacts, and peek into real working labs. For more on the @burkemuseum, watch the full film on IGTV or visit link in bio to read more at @archrecordmag!

node.text: “This cabin serves as the ideal antidote to my daily life, where I am constantly working on intense projects, going to meetings, and traveling. Watch the full film on IGTV.

node.text: “I think of the landscape, architecture, and art as one unified, harmonious environment – each overlaps the other. Architectural features stretch out into the landscape. Art pieces enrich the interiors through color, form and the stories they tell. Everything is woven into everything else.” –Jim Olson, FAIA. “Jim Olson: Building • Nature • Art" showcases some of Jim's recent projects, while illustrating the key philosophies and guiding principles he has spent more than fifty years refining: the aesthetic interplay of art, nature, and architecture. Watch the full film on IGTV.

node.text: Today we’re revisiting “Welcome to the Fifth Façade,” a conceptual exploration by Design Principal Alan Maskin. Beginning as a research project, the idea expanded to include a mural, a science fiction story, a graphic novel and, eventually, a film. “Welcome to the Fifth Façade” went on to win first place in Blank Space’s (@blankspacenyc) 2016 Fairy Tales Competition, the world’s largest architectural ideas contest. Click above to watch the full short film on IGTV.

node.text: This month we celebrate the third anniversary of the Space Needle's (@spaceneedle) public unveiling! The new design includes the world’s first rotating glass floor on the 500-foot level, floor-to-ceiling glass barriers with integral glass benches on the observation deck, a new steel and glass stairway with a glass-floored oculus connecting all three floors, and revised interiors throughout the “top house” of the Needle. Though careful coordination across the full project team allowed parts of Seattle's iconic tower to remain open during construction, this month marked the first time visitors could enjoy the fully revised Space Needle experience (with some additional efforts continuing behind the scenes). Visit link in bio to learn more!

node.text: Earlier this week, the CheckMate Winery (@checkmatewinery) Pop-Up celebrated its fourth anniversary! node.text: Olson Kundig is excited for the return of Seattle Design Festival (@SeaDesignFest) next month, one of our favorite local events! Themed EMERGE, the 2021 festival seeks to inspire action, addressing the consequences of the pandemic to nurture new possibilities. This year, we partnered with Camp United We Stand, Dowbuilt (@dowbuilt) and ARUP (@arupamericas) to design and build Homebase, a lightweight modular shelter made from commodity materials for under $1,000, and featuring repurposed plywood murals removed from International District storefronts. After the festival, the prototype will be adopted by Camp United We Stand for use in their self-managed, safe, community-supported encampments. Homebase and other installations will be open to the public during the two-day SDF Block Party, August 21-22, at Lake Union Park in Seattle. We look forward to taking you behind the scenes in the coming weeks – for now, visit link in bio for more information about #SDFHomebase and the Seattle Design Festival!

node.text: “In mountaineering, the summit is never the goal – it’s great if it happens, but if you’re not there to feed your passion and enjoy the journey, then summitting means nothing. You have to be comfortable being uncomfortable, to be nimble and able to pivot and adapt,” Olson Kundig CEO/owner Hemanshu “HP” Parwani told Monograph (@monographhq) during a recent Best Practice virtual chat. “In design, if you’re not enjoying the process, if the client isn’t happy with the process, that reflects in the final project.” Visit link in bio to watch a recording of their full conversation!

node.text: "I first laid eyes on Bruno Grimmek’s wholesale flower market, completed in 1965, on a site tour for the design competition’s short-listed teams. It was love at first sight: an enormous, unheated concrete shell with 5 curved light scoops that run the entire length of the ceiling. Every decision about inserting a museum as a building within this concrete husk was a direct conversation between what was then, and what is now." –Alan Maskin (@alanmaskin), Design Principal. Alan recently joined host Oli Stratford on an episode of The Crit podcast (@thecritpodcast) to chat about ANOHA (@anohaberlin), now open at the Jewish Museum Berlin. Visit link in bio to listen!

node.text: Recently, Copine (@copineproject) celebrated their fifth anniversary – and shared that they will reopen for dine-in service on July 15! Designed by principal/owner Kirsten Ring Murray (@kirsten3000), Copine features a balance of traditional and modern, reclaimed and new, to create a refined, human-scaled space where their contemporary American cuisine takes center stage. We’ve enjoyed Copine’s takeaway suppers throughout this past year, and we can’t wait to visit for an in-person meal again soon. Visit link in bio to learn more!
